metadata.name: CHIP #88
metadata.description:
A CHIP is being constructed by using two brushes that are painting on the board through deterministic noise, and then turned squared and pixelated and blended into each other, with colours selected from 21 different colour schemes. How many iterations, and the speed and size of the added parts determines the final composition. 

You can stop the iterations by pressing S, and download the current composition by hitting D, and restart/reload the iterations by pressing R.

Notes
The thumbnail generation takes a while and the render/iterations in non-GPU browser can be quite slow. Chrome/Firefox recommended.

metadata.name: gate gallery #31
metadata.description:
A person cannot always evaluate something by one example. After drying one song from an album, you can't say "cool album".

What if the album is one story? Do you understand what I mean? I cut off different patterns with the same base lines and already created a whole story.

Sometimes by changing the angle of view, you change everything you see. Perhaps if you saw my usual artwork, you would not notice the essence of generativity without these lines.

metadata.name: CR Art Sessions //2 #138
metadata.description:
Grayscale, Hold the Line, and Mondrian walk into a bar. The bartender looks up and says, "What is this, some kind of art project?"

Grayscale responds, "No, we're just here for a drink."

Hold the Line adds, "But we can definitely add some color to the place if you want."

Mondrian chimes in, "I prefer to keep things simple and stick to the basics."

The bartender shakes his head and says, "I'll be the judge of that. What can I get you all?"

Grayscale orders a Guinness, Hold the Line asks for a gin and tonic, and Mondrian asks for a glass of white wine.

The bartender serves up the drinks and says, "That will be $15.50, please."

Grayscale pulls out a twenty-dollar bill and hands it to the bartender, saying, "Keep the change."

The bartender thanks him and says, "Thanks, Grayscale. You always know how to liven up the place."

Hold the Line raises his glass and says, "Cheers to that!"

Mondrian nods and clinks glasses with the others, and the three of them enjoy their drinks and the rest of their evening at the bar.

-----

Press "e" to save a png (3240*4500 or 4500*3240 px) while in live mode.

-----

Artwork by @cristianrohr (2022)

Made with P5js and <3.

metadata.name: SPOT #209
metadata.description:
A study of circles, sizes, lines, colors, grains and alphas. The composition consists solely of 2d shapes but generates a 3d look. The base colors use a random chromaticity factor which results in a wild range of combinations. There is a 70% change on a dark background and 30% on a light background also 15% change on black and white. 

Press s in live mode for a 2000x2800 download

Download a higher resolution by adding to the URL:
&density=2 / &density=3 / &density=4

Lammetje December 2022

metadata.name: Hydro Gen #10
metadata.description:
Against the backdrop of texts about valuing water, Hydro Gen charts the ecological devastation and eventual revival of the Tisza river following what has been called one of the gravest environmental disasters in central Europe since Chernobyl.

Nature and humans here are bound within a single frame — havoc in the ecological system activates the breakdown of meaning in the human signifying system of language, but hidden in the wave of ecological disaster is a (re)generative love poem to water that bears witness to its multifaceted beauty and power. A second poem is generated as a soundtrack based on the displayed background text.

- - - - - CLICK TO START SOUND - - - - -

Hydro Gen is a collaborative work conceptualized and developed over the course of one week as part of NFT DEB Generative Dimensions 2022 Hackathon and Conference.

Kalen Iwamoto, lead artist, director

Vitalii Shumanskyi, lead programmer

Nayven Vignette, audio programmer

Tamás Béke, data analysis and visualization

metadata.name: NEW TERRITORIES #51
metadata.description:
On desktop, open project in live view
Rotate and zoom with the mouse to explore the model
Click “S” to download STL 3D model file
Click “P” to download PNG file (3600x3600)


New Territories

New Territories is the sequel to Cityblocks. In this series, urban ensembles are generated with a simple click. With each iteration appears a new densely built city block. Graced with impeccable geometrical lines, devoid of any human presence, these buildings remind us of brutalist utopias like Le Corbusier’s Cité radieuse or Niemeyer’s Brasilia. But despite their clearly modernist feel, there is something hauntingly primitive about them. They could be either New Mexican adobe pueblos, Minoan palaces, or Turkish troglodyte dwellings. Both carved and sculpted, these Ghormenghasts of concrete float in a realm out of time, like in some architect’s dream.

The purpose of this creative work is to generate 3D architectural projects that could be implemented in the real world. The accelerating lives that we live, complicated by growing and unpredictable environmental crises, call for an enhanced capacity to come up quickly with new architectural solutions adapted to different contexts. From computer assisted design to 3D printing, from augmented reality to real-life housing, from sculpture to architecture, this work aims at bridging the gap between the virtual and the tangible.

Working as a visual artist, David Umemoto draws inspiration from his training as an architect. He has been using low-tech methods for a long time, refining his talent for elegant simple shapes and combinatory constructions. Now, poured concrete and home-made moulds are giving way to zero-gravity rotating models. The skills he developed while working with real objects find a new playground in the virtual realm.

metadata.name: Lucky Oracles #708
metadata.description:
"Lucky Oracles" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

Eko33, is a Swiss-French generative artist who has been at the forefront of digital arts since 1999 when he started writing code to create generative artworks and installations. He made his debut using a Commodore SX-64 and floppy disks. Since then, his work has been exhibited in Museums, International art fairs, and biennales. His work is focused on nonfigurative, generative art while using custom algorithms and innovative technology.

Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/ Official Twitter account: https://twitter.com/eko3316 Official Instagram account: https://www.instagram.com/eko33studio/ https://linktr.ee/eko33 "I create deterministic generative art based on crypto hash seeds. Maximizing algorithmic diversity."

If you want to receive an e-mail alert when I release new artwork subscribe here => https://eko33.com/email-alerts

metadata.name: Resilience  #245
metadata.description:
Resilience is a collection of endless architectures.
In a resilient generative system composed of multiple compatible parts, real-time information exchange enables open reconfigurations and continuous discrete adjustments. Sometimes vague and fuzzy, sometimes real and tangible, they reveal different readings of architectural complexity and scale: from city plans to floor plans and details to sections and elevations.

Resilience comes in a variety of polychrome palettes, ascii glyphs, and styles. 
To enjoy it in full-screen mode, press the left mouse button in live mode, for a monochrome look press 'b'. Made with P5js.

Resilience Generative Token by @grasser_alex 2022

metadata.name: Pillars of Tomorrow #74
metadata.description:
Our vision is to create meaningful generative artworks that express human sentiments about their social experiences.

We’re currently focused on experiences centered around celebration, and we’ve chosen a theme that connects people through music.
Music has the power to evoke a wide range of emotions within us, especially when experienced through a collective experience.

We wanted to generate an artistic script that visually captures these expressions. 

Our first music NFT collection reflects human sentiments towards Tomorrowland 2022. 
It's a creative collaboration with dahleea, an artist dedicated to colors, who gave us the inspiration for the visuals you are seeing through one of her beautiful and colorful artworks.

Coding, music, and art collide to recreate emotions expressed by people coming together from all over the world to share music and connection at one of the world’s leading music festivals. 

The creative process:

Data was collected via emotion analysis using Twitter’s API. Our data is derived from emotion analysis models to extract the emotion scores (Happiness, Anger, Sadness, Fear, and Surprise) from 105,762 tweets, written in English, and containing mention of ‘Tomorrowland' between July 15, 2022, to August 8, 2022. 

Our analysis demonstrated the following emotions:

Happiness: 38%
Anger 8%
Sadness: 26%
Fear: 28%

Music:

In Pillars of Tomorrow, there are 4 instruments: bass, piano, percussion (hi-hat, kick, snare, claps, fx sounds), and a quiet pad. All the rhythms are self-written using Ableton, exported, and randomly selected to create the backbone of our generative music NFT.

This music piece has 4 different parts (basic, drop, break, after-drop) which are looped 3 times. All parts include different rhythm variations which are chosen randomly. 

The generative harmony is present in the basic and after-drop parts. The key to generating harmony is using the emotion percentages above as possibilities for the next piano chord and melody to sound happy or sad.  
We chose to distort our bass sound according to anger trait values, as distortion can turn a mild bass into an aggressive one. 

Finally, there is also an emotion of surprise, which is associated with a special background and the sound of bells ringing.  The surprise element trait of the mints will be revealed after the Pillars of Tomorrow collection is fully minted.

We wanted to make a dynamic collection that would give you the feeling of a live music event, an interactive experience. A big stage flowing with music and diverse human expressions.

c-camera start/stop
p pause (or play)

space (play/stop)

l (change where the camera look)

Arrow Up (View pillars from above)
Arrow down (go to starting position)
Arrow left/right (camera moving direction)

AWSD work as arrows as well
scroll (Zoom In/Out)

enter (screenshot)

For an optimal experience, we recommend using Google Chrome.

#CodingIsArt

metadata.name: Perspective #53
metadata.description:
A few primitives and a lot of points.

Warning: This piece is GPU intensive, it may not render on lower end devices.

Keys
s: Take a screenshot
space: Pause/Play the animation.
r: Play a new animation
↑: Increase point alpha
↓: Decrease point alpha
→: Increase point density
←: Decrease point density

URL Params
w: Width of the canvas - (ex, w=1024) - [0-2048]
h: Height of the canvas - (ex, h=1024) - [0-2048]
a: To set the alpha for the points - [0.0-1.0]
p: To set the total number of points to draw (in millions) [1-8]
s: Make the visual static - (ex, s=1)

metadata.name: TIMEFRAMES #300
metadata.description:
‘What if you could take a photo of time?’

As a photographer myself, the act of taking photos is the act of freezing moments of time. Moments that will no longer ever be here. Each layer represents not only 3 aspects of time (hours, minutes and seconds) but also a very important aspect of photography: the light. Combining these two instances: the visual interpretation of light and the generative aspect of time - I present ‘TIMEFRAMES’.

12 selected colors. 5,688,900 possible combinations.

The less layers the rarer - ranging from 100% to 18%
All timeframes that have 42 on it like 4:20:00, 4:42:42, 4:20:42 are rarer - ranging from 50% to 42%
The darker the colors the rarer - ranging from 100% to 89%

Click on the image to Download. Created with @PureSpider’s template.

José Gasparian.
2022.
